<SPAN STYLE="position:absolute; left:374px; top:690px; width:312px; font-family:Comic Sans MS; font-weight:bold; text-align:center; font-size:12px; color:#000000;">
A Reminder from the Editor's Desk
<SPAN STYLE="font-family:Comic Sans MS; font-weight:bold; text-align:center; font-size:11px; color:#000000;">

<BR>
</SPAN>
<SPAN STYLE="font-family:Comic Sans MS; font-weight:normal; text-align:left; font-size:9px; color:#000000;">
There may be some who are not familiar with our tradition of personal anonymity at the public level. &nbsp;"Our public relations policy is based on attraction rather than promotion..." &nbsp;Thus, we remind AA speakers and AA members not to be photographed, videotaped or identified by full name on audiotapes and in published or broadcast reports of our meetings, including those reports on new media technologies such as the Internet.
<BR>
The assurance of anonymity is essential in our efforts to help other problem drinkers who may wish to share our recovery program with us. And our tradition of anonymity reminds us that "AA principles come before personalities."
</SPAN>
